{\line }

{\line }
Everything seemed as it should be; everyone seemed professional, going about their work. It somehow felt wrong for an army to be this distant, so indifferent to an enemy that was in fact their own people, though wildly misled and utterly wrong in their decision to upset their way of life with shattering consequences. Or so Tyrpledge felt. He didn\uc1\u8217't know and could not know though, what his men thought and felt. He\uc1\u8217'd have to wait for them to show their true demeanor and spirit in the ultimate test: battle.
{\line }

{\line }
